Objective¶

The objective of this project is to use the data provided from UCI data archive to classify and predict heart disease in patients based on the different variable parameters and using the different techniques learned in class.

Dataset description¶

According to the Centers for Disease Control (CDC), about 610,000 people die of heart disease in the United States every yearthats 1 in every 4 deaths (CDC, 2017). Heart disease are a large problem for not only the US, but the world as they deal with human life and can affect the friends and family of anyone. This is why as researchers, we wonder: could we use the techniques we learned in class with data on patients to predict heart disease?

This project uses data from the Heart Disease Prediction heart-disease directory data on Kaggle. The data comes from credible data sources on heart disease and features 14 attributes.

We can see that some of the strongest correlated values with heart disease (target) are 'cp' (chest pain) and 'thalach' (maximum heart rate achieved). Let's move onto some data mining.

Data mining¶

Since our objective is to build a classifier for predicting/classifying whether or not a patient will have heart disease, we will use a Decision Tree Classifier to accomplish this. Since we are using the Decision Tree Classifier we do not necessarily have to scale these features. However, let's change some of our categorical variables.

In [371]:
df2 = pd.get_dummies(data=df,columns=['cp','restecg','slope','ca','thal'],drop_first=True)

Introducing Grid Search For Optimizing Parameters¶

Looking at our accuracy for the training set, we can definitely see that the model overfit. Lets try using gridsearch to find the best parameters for the model:

    'min_samples_split': np.linspace(2,40,40,dtype=int)}]

We managed to bring up our accuracy a bit and slighly reduce overfitting. Not only that, we also managed to decrease the number of false negatives, which is very important in this kind of analysis. We would not want to tell our patient that he/she most likely does not have heart disease, only to find out that he/she does that could be fatal.

Image(graph[0].create_png())
Out[765]:

So in results it seems that we lost around 5% of information when reducing dimensions from 22 to 2/3. The PCA with n_components of 3 seem to have done better than it did with n_components = 2, but that's to be expected since we're dealing with information loss through compression. Let's try the ensemble technique "Random Forest Decision Classifier" and see if we can improve the model.

After trying different parameters, we can see that we have better results with the Random Forest Classifier. All in all, although there are more parameters we could explore, there is an endless amount of fine tuning that goes into making sure a model is completely ready, and I feel that without more data or other techniques the current ceiling for accuracy is approximately 80-85%.
